  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Reflections During Illness
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Year after year I have squandered the seasons of the civil service exams,
    yet in my twilight years my body still holds vigor.
    The examinations have always favored only the talented—
    who among the great ministers would recommend the mediocre?

    The great whale strains to leap, but the waves have run dry.
    The ailing crane yearns to soar, yet its wings are broken.

    I have long possessed a place of retreat in the eastern rivers,
    and now, with whitened hair, I return at last—
    how pitiable is this fate of mine.
  footnotes:
    - The 'great whale' and 'ailing crane' are metaphors for the poet's own unfulfilled ambitions and physical decline
    - The reference to 'eastern rivers' evokes the classical ideal of hermitic withdrawal from public life
